The paper deals with algorithmic problems related to graph classes of bounded rankwidth and treewidth, which are typical topics in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also involves structural properties of graphs and their modifications, which are relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG) and complexity theory (cs.CC). Lastly, the paper discusses the Exponential Time Hypothesis, which is a central conjecture in computational complexity theory, and its implications on the running time of the algorithm, which is related to graph theory (cs.GT).
